Using all the points of a circle for collision detection is highly inefficient and unnecessary. In computational geometry, you don't need to check every point on the circle to detect collisions. For circle-to-point and circle-to-circle collisions, you can rely on mathematical properties of circles.

Here are the implementations you're looking for:

```cpp
#include <cmath>
#include <vector>

// Assuming Point class is already defined like this:
class Point {
public:
    int x, y;

    Point(int x = 0, int y = 0) : x(x), y(y) {}

    // Euclidean distance squared between two points (to avoid sqrt call)
    int DistanceSquared(const Point& other) const {
        int dx = x - other.x;
        int dy = y - other.y;
        return dx * dx + dy * dy;
    }
};

class Circle {
public:
    // Existing members and methods...

    bool ContainsPoint(const Point& point) const {
        // Check if the point is inside the circle by comparing the square of the radius
        // with the squared distance from the point to the circle's center.
        return center.DistanceSquared(point) <= (radius * radius);
    }

    bool IntersectsCircle(const Circle& other) const {
        // Two circles intersect when the distance between their centers
        // is less than the sum of their radii.

        // First, calculate the squared distance between the center points
        int distanceSquared = center.DistanceSquared(other.GetCenter());

        // Calculate the squared sum of the radii
        int radiiSumSquared = (radius + other.GetRadius()) * (radius + other.GetRadius());

        // If the squared distance is less than or equal to the squared sum
        // of the radii, the circles intersect.
        return distanceSquared <= radiiSumSquared;
    }
    // Other members and methods...
};
```

In the above `ContainsPoint` method, we avoid the use of `sqrt` by comparing the squared distance to the squared radius since `sqrt` is an expensive operation and the relative comparison is still valid when using squares.

For `IntersectsCircle`, we use a similar approach. We calculate the distance squared between the two center points and compare it to the square of the sum of the radii.

Please remove the dependency on `GetPoints` for these methods if it is used to get all the points of a circle; instead just calculate the distance between points using the simple `DistanceSquared` method in the `Point` class.

In object-oriented programming, duplication is often solved using inheritance. However, in the case of a simple utility like `DistanceSquared`, using inheritance might be an overkill and may unnecessarily complicate the class hierarchy. Instead, you can use templates to create a generic function that works for both `int` and `float` and doesn't require a common base class.

Below is an example of how to define a generic `DistanceSquared` function outside of the `Point` class, which can handle both `Point` (assumed to have integer coordinates) and `FPoint` (assumed to have floating-point coordinates).

```cpp
#include <type_traits>
#include <cmath>

template <typename T>
class TPoint {
public:
    T x, y;

    TPoint(T x = 0, T y = 0) : x(x), y(y) {}

    // Remove the default copy constructor and assignment operator to avoid slicing
    TPoint(const TPoint&) = default;
    TPoint& operator=(const TPoint&) = default;
};

// Generic function to calculate the squared distance between two points
template <typename T>
T DistanceSquared(const TPoint<T>& a, const TPoint<T>& b) {
    T dx = a.x - b.x;
    T dy = a.y - b.y;
    return dx * dx + dy * dy;
}

using Point = TPoint<int>;        // Specialization for int
using FPoint = TPoint<float>;     // Specialization for float

// Updated Circle classes:

template <typename T>
class TCircle {
public:
    TCircle(T centerX, T centerY, T radius) : center(centerX, centerY), radius(radius) {}
    TCircle(const TPoint<T>& center, T radius) : center(center), radius(radius) {}

    bool ContainsPoint(const TPoint<T>& point) const {
        return DistanceSquared(center, point) <= (radius * radius);
    }

    bool IntersectsCircle(const TCircle& other) const {
        T distanceSquared = DistanceSquared(center, other.center);
        T radiiSum = radius + other.radius;
        return distanceSquared <= (radiiSum * radiiSum);
    }

    // Other members and methods...
private:
    TPoint<T> center;
    T radius;
};

using Circle = TCircle<int>;
using FCircle = TCircle<float>;
```

In this example:
- `TPoint` is a template class that can represent a point in 2D space using both `int` and `float`.
- `DistanceSquared` is a template function that calculates the squared distance between two points of the same type. It accepts two `TPoint` instances and calculates the distance squared between them.
- `TCircle` is a template class that can represent a circle using both `int` and `float`. It has methods for containment and intersection checks similar to the `Circle` class. It uses `DistanceSquared` for calculations.
- `Point` and `Circle` are type definitions (type aliases) for `TPoint<int>` and `TCircle<int>`, respectively.
- `FPoint` and `FCircle` are type definitions for `TPoint<float>` and `TCircle<float>`, respectively.

This template-based approach allows you to avoid duplication of logic while also being able to work generically with different numeric types without unnecessary inheritance. It's a clean way to support both `int` and `float` (or potentially other numeric types) without separate but identical implementations for `Point` and `FPoint`.

