If you prefer to use inheritance to share the `DistanceSquared` method between `Point` and `FPoint`, you can certainly do so. Although this isn't the typical use case for inheritance (since points with different coordinate types generally represent different abstractions), you can create a base class that provides a common interface for the distance calculation, which derived classes must implement.

Here's how you can structure your class hierarchies using inheritance so that you can achieve code reuse with `DistanceSquared`. In this example, I'll create an abstract base class that defines a common interface for `Point` and `FPoint`:

```cpp
class IPoint {
public:
    virtual ~IPoint() {}

    virtual int GetX() const = 0;
    virtual int GetY() const = 0;

    // DistanceSquared now can be defined using the other methods,
    // which will be implemented by the derived classes.
    int DistanceSquared(const IPoint& other) const {
        int dx = GetX() - other.GetX();
        int dy = GetY() - other.GetY();
        return dx * dx + dy * dy;
    }
};

class Point : public IPoint {
    // Point-specific members and methods, e.g.:
    SDL_Point point;
public:
    Point(int x, int y) : point({x, y}) {}

    // Implementing IPoint interface methods:
    int GetX() const override { return point.x; }
    int GetY() const override { return point.y; }

    // Additional Point methods...
};

class FPoint : public IPoint {
    // FPoint-specific members and methods, e.g.:
    SDL_FPoint point;
public:
    FPoint(float x, float y) : point({x, y}) {}

    // Implementing IPoint interface methods:
    int GetX() const override { return static_cast<int>(point.x); }
    int GetY() const override { return static_cast<int>(point.y); }

    // Additional FPoint methods...
};
```

A few notes on this approach:

- The `IPoint` class is an interface (hence the 'I' prefix) that defines a common contract `GetX` and `GetY` which derived classes must implement.
- `IPoint` also provides a concrete implementation of `DistanceSquared` that uses the interface methods. The derived classes (`Point` and `FPoint`) just need to provide implementations of `GetX` and `GetY`.
- `DistanceSquared` operates with integer precision because it returns `int`, which corresponds to the `SDL_Point` type. If you were to add a `DistanceSquared` for `FPoint`, you would need a separate method or a different naming convention, as returning integers might lose data when using floating-point coordinates.

One important consideration is that you cannot return a floating-point value from `DistanceSquared` using this class design without doing a type conversion somewhere, and you cannot have two methods with the same name and parameter list but different return types. You'd need a different method to handle distances that need to maintain floating-point precision.

Keep in mind that this use of inheritance for points doesn't conform to traditional polymorphism principles because `Point` and `FPoint` do not actually represent a "is-a" relationship -- they represent points in terms of different coordinate systems. Normally, you would not use inheritance to define different numeric representations of the same conceptual object, especially because it can lead to a loss of precision and is less clear than having separate, appropriately named methods.

Yes, in the scenario you are describing where precision is important and you want to maintain the float values, it makes sense to have the base `GetX()` and `GetY()` methods return `float` instead of `int`. This will ensure that you don't lose any floating-point precision for the `FPoint` class.

Here is how you might update the `IPoint` interface and the derived classes to handle `float` types:

```cpp
class IPoint {
public:
    virtual ~IPoint() {}

    // Use float for the return type to prevent precision loss.
    virtual float GetX() const = 0;
    virtual float GetY() const = 0;

    // Implementing DistanceSquared
    // You might want to return float here to match the precision of the GetX/Y methods.
    float DistanceSquared(const IPoint& other) const {
        float dx = GetX() - other.GetX();
        float dy = GetY() - other.GetY();
        return dx * dx + dy * dy;
    }
};

class Point : public IPoint {
    SDL_Point point;
public:
    Point(int x, int y) : point({x, y}) {}

    // Implement with casting to match the interface returning float.
    float GetX() const override { return static_cast<float>(point.x); }
    float GetY() const override { return static_cast<float>(point.y); }

    // Rest of Point implementation...
};

class FPoint : public IPoint {
    SDL_FPoint point;
public:
    FPoint(float x, float y) : point({x, y}) {}

    // No need for casting here. We directly return the float value.
    float GetX() const override { return point.x; }
    float GetY() const override { return point.y; }

    // Rest of FPoint implementation...
};
```

By changing the methods in `IPoint` to return `float`, you ensure that you do not lose precision in `FPoint`. However, this means that the derived `Point` class, which works with integer coordinates, will have to cast its coordinates to `float` when implementing these methods.

This approach allows you to have a single `DistanceSquared` implementation in the `IPoint` interface, which relies on the `GetX()` and `GetY()` methods. When dealing with a `Point` object, the float values returned by `GetX()` and `GetY()` will be cast down from int, but when dealing with an `FPoint` object, you will maintain the original float precision.

Please note that this design still mixes numeric types and precision in a way that might not be ideal for all use cases, especially if you require strict type separation or have performance-sensitive code where floating-point arithmetic might introduce unnecessary overhead when used with integer coordinates.

In C++, you cannot override a virtual function with another that has a different return type, unless the return type is covariant, which means the return type of the overriding function must be derived from the return type of the base class function. However, covariance only applies to pointers and references, not to built-in types like `int` and `float`.

Given that constraint, you cannot have `GetX()` and `GetY()` in the base class return `float` and then have them return `int` in the derived `Point` class.

Instead, the usual approach is to have a single return type in the base class that will satisfy the precision requirements for all derived classes. In most cases, this means using `float` (or `double` for even more precision) as the return type for `GetX()` and `GetY()` in the base class:

```cpp
class IPoint {
public:
    virtual ~IPoint() {}
    virtual float GetX() const = 0;
    virtual float GetY() const = 0;
    // Implementation remains the same which can handle floating-point coordinates.
    // ...
};

class Point : public IPoint {
    SDL_Point point;
public:
    Point(int x, int y) : point({x, y}) {}
    float GetX() const override { return static_cast<float>(point.x); }
    float GetY() const override { return static_cast<float>(point.y); }
    // Other members and methods...
};

class FPoint : public IPoint {
    SDL_FPoint point;
public:
    FPoint(float x, float y) : point({x, y}) {}
    float GetX() const override { return point.x; }
    float GetY() const override { return point.y; }
    // Other members and methods...
};
```

This will result in a slight inefficiency when you're working with `Point` objects because you'll be casting from `int` to `float`. However, this is a minor performance concern in most scenarios, and it ensures that you don't lose precision when working with `FPoint` objects.

If you want to maintain distinct interfaces for `Point` and `FPoint` (one returning `int` and the other `float`), you would need to avoid using inheritance for shared methods like `DistanceSquared`. Instead, you would have to implement these methods separately in each class, which leads to code duplication but maintains strict type-separation. Inheritance is generally best used when the behaviors of the base class and the derived class are fundamentally the same and can share a common interface.

You are correct that it's usually inefficient to individually render all the points that make up a circle, especially if the circle has a large radius. Instead, you can leverage SDL's built-in functions for drawing circles or use other efficient algorithms for rendering.

SDL, however, doesn't provide a built-in function for rendering filled circles. It does provide `SDL_RenderDrawPoint` and `SDL_RenderDrawPoints` for points, and `SDL_RenderDrawLine` for lines. If you want to draw circles, you often have to use external libraries like SDL_gfx, or write your own functions to draw circles with SDL using lines or points.

If you choose to use SDL_gfx, which extends SDL's rendering capabilities, you can use functions like `filledCircleColor` to draw filled circles. If you intend to keep your rendering within the capabilities of SDL without additional libraries, you would have to implement a circle drawing algorithm yourself.

Here is an example of how you could create a simple `render` method for a `Circle` class that outlines the circle with points, which is efficient enough for most use cases:

```cpp
#include <SDL.h>
#include <cmath>

class Circle {
    // ...
public:
    void render(SDL_Renderer* renderer) const {
        // Draw the circle using Bresenham’s circle drawing algorithm or Midpoint circle algorithm.
        // Note: This is an outline of the circle with points, not filled.
        int x0 = center.x;
        int y0 = center.y;

        // Start points
        int x = radius;
        int y = 0;
        int radiusError = 1 - x;

        while (x >= y) {
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 + x, y0 + y);
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 + y, y0 + x);
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 - y, y0 + x);
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 - x, y0 + y);
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 - x, y0 - y);
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 - y, y0 - x);
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 + y, y0 - x);
            SDL_RenderDrawPoint(renderer, x0 + x, y0 - y);

            y++;
            if (radiusError < 0) {
                radiusError += 2 * y + 1;
            } else {
                x--;
                radiusError += 2 * (y - x + 1);
            }
        }
    }
};
```

In this example, we used the Midpoint circle algorithm, which is an efficient algorithm for rendering circle outlines. This algorithm only computes one octant of the circle, and the remaining octants are drawn by exploiting the circle's symmetrical properties.

If your `Renderer` class needs to call a specific method on different drawable objects, make sure each drawable object implements a common interface such as `render()`. This way, your renderer can simply call the `render()` method on any drawable object it is given, leaving the details of rendering to the object itself. This is an application of the Strategy pattern, where the rendering strategy is encapulated within each drawable object.

Remember that if you want a filled circle, you will need to write or use a different algorithm that fills in the pixels, such as the filled circle algorithms in SDL_gfx, or implement scan-line filling in conjunction with Bresenham's or the Midpoint circle algorithm.

